@node Requirements "Requirements"
@next Features
@prev MUI
@toc  Main

				@{b}Requirements@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    @{b}Address@{ub} is a very non-demanding program when it comes to what it 
    requires in the form of hardware and software to run. However, it
    has a few fundamental requirements:

    * You need an Amiga.

    * You need MUI 3.8.

    * Since MUI needs AmigaOS 2.0 or higher, so does @{b}Address@{ub}.
      @{i}However@{ui}, if your system is not localized you might experience a not 
      entirely correct sorting of the names in the listview. If your system
      @{b}is@{ub} localized there is still a chance part of the sorting isn't totally 
      correct for all languages. By installing the proper "#?.language" file
      that is included in this archive, you will in all probability achieve
      an accurate sorting. To find out more about this, click @{"here" link Sorting}.

    * You don't really @{b}need@{ub} a harddisk to run @{b}Address@{ub} but since it's pretty
      difficult, if at all possible, to run MUI from floppy disks and since
      @{b}Address@{ub} needs MUI you can figure out the rest for yourself.

    * If you would like to make a hardcopy of your data you need a printer.

    That's about it! If you experience some problems with @{b}Address@{ub} on your
    computer and all crucial demands above are fulfilled, please don't
    hesitate to contact @{"me" link Author} immediately; that way perhaps we can work out 
    a solution together.

@endnode

@node Features "Features"
@next Installation
@prev Requirements
@toc  Main

				@{b}Features@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    Below are a few features that I think best describe @{b}Address@{ub}.

    @{i}The program ...@{ui}

    * allows you to store a wide range of data about a particular person.

    * has a very neat GUI (Graphical User Interface) which makes sure that
      every function is easy to find and understand in a fast and effective
      way.

    * offers the possibility to save the data to a database. The only limit
      as to the size of this database is the available space on your 
      harddisk/floppy disk.

    * stores all changes to the database the split-second you confirm them,
      e.g., by clicking "OK". This minimizes the risk of a computer crash
      or Guru Meditation causing any errors in your valuable database. This
      also means that you don't have to worry your head about saving the
      data, it is done completely automatically the minute you add the entry
      to the database.

    * permits you to print a person's data using your printer.

    * automatically sorts the names in the @{"listview" link The_Main_Window} alphabetically, which
      makes it very easy to find a particular entry.

    * can be fully controlled using the keyboard as well as the mouse.

    * is very small and thus very fast.

    * will be continually supported by @{"me" link Author}.

    * is a completely Swedish product. :-)

@endnode

@node Installation "Installation"
@next The_Main_Window
@prev Features
@toc  Main

				@{b}Installation@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    The best way to install @{b}Address@{ub} is to run the program @{b}Install-Address@{ub}
    from your Workbench by double-clicking the appropriate icon. This file 
    uses Commodore's @{b}Installer@{ub} and performs the installation procedure with
    as little input from you as possible. I have encountered many programs 
    with defective installation procedures in my days; the @{b}Address@{ub} 
    installation script shall NOT be another one of those faulty procedures.

    Commodore's @{b}Installer@{ub} is not included in this archive, but unless you
    already have it - which I suspect many of you do - the program is easily
    obtained from Aminet and other sources.

    Good luck with the installation!

@endnode

@node The_Main_Window "The Main Window"
@next The_New_Window
@prev Installation
@toc  Main

				@{b}The Main Window@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    @{b}Address@{ub} consists of several different windows which all have different
    meanings and functions. When you first start @{b}Address@{ub} you are greeted by
    the Main Window, which is split into two parts.

    The upper one, @{b}Records@{ub}, contains a listview. This is the core of @{b}Address@{ub}.
    Here is where you will see the names of all the people currently stored
    in your @{b}Address@{ub} database. By double-clicking any of the names the Show
    Window will unfold in front of your anxious eyes and you will see every-
    thing you have stored about this particular person. You can achieve the
    same effect by clicking the "Show" button in the lower part of the
    window, under @{b}Operations@{ub}. Of course you can also press <S> or <s> on
    your keyboard to activate the Show Window.

    The entries in the listview are automatically sorted alphabetically
    whenever you create them, but if you still would like to rearrange the
    order, just select a record and drag it with your trusty mouse to a
    place of your choice.

    There are a few other interesting buttons in the lower part of the 
    window, i.e., the @{b}Operations@{ub} part:

    * @{u}N@{uu}ew, which triggers and opens the @{"New Window" link The_New_Window}, where you can create
      a new record, i.e., input data to store a new person in your database.

    * @{u}E@{uu}dit, which triggers and opens the @{"Edit Window" link The_Edit_Window}, where you can alter
      any previously stored information. Thus, if your friend changes his
      street address, all you need to do is enter this window and change the 
      "Street Address" field accordingly.

    * @{u}S@{uu}how, which triggers and opens the @{"Show Window" link The_Show_Window}, which we talked about
      above. The @{"New Window" link The_New_Window} and the @{"Edit Window" link The_Edit_Window} are pretty alike in certain
      respects; the Show Window differs slightly in its layout and design. 
      This is due to my ambition to make every window as well-organized as 
      possible. The windows are also designed to fit their purpose in as 
      smooth a way as possible.

    * @{u}P@{uu}rint, which triggers a print-out to your printer of the stored in-
      formation about the selected person. There is not much more to say
      about this function, it's pretty self-explanatory. Try it!

    * @{u}R@{uu}emove, which deletes all data about the selected person from your
      database. Note: There is NO way to restore the information you are
      deleting, it's gone forever the second you activate this button.

    You will notice there is no "Quit" button. The reason for this is I've
    put that function in the menu instead. This is rather insignificant,
    but you have your basic options:

    * @{b}About@{ub}, which triggers and opens an "About" window about the program.
      Here you'll find my e-mail address and some other, probably not too
      interesting, data.

    * @{b}About MUI@{ub}..., which triggers and opens the "About MUI" window, a window
      you might recognize from other programs.

    * @{b}Settings... -> MUI...@{ub}, which triggers and opens the MUI User Interface
      Settings for @{b}Address@{ub}. Here you can configure the Graphical User Inter-
      face (GUI) of @{b}Address@{ub} in more ways than most people thought possible.

    * @{b}Quit@{ub}, which would be a rather appropriate menu item to choose if you'd
      like to quit @{b}Address@{ub}. Actually, I can't think of any reason to do this, 
      but the human mind works in mysterious ways. :-)

    You can reach the listview and all the buttons in the program through 
    the keyboard and the same goes for the menu items. Try <TAB>, notice the
    underlining of certain letters and look to the right of the menu items, 
    and you'll understand what I mean.

    Have fun!

@endnode

@node The_New_Window "The New Window"
@next The_Edit_Window
@prev The_Main_Window
@toc  Main

				@{b}The New Window@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    Whenever you want to insert a new record into your database, this is the 
    window you should open. Here you can input lots of information about a 
    person, such as his name, his e-mail address and perhaps the number to 
    his cellular phone.

    When you open this window the cursor is automatically placed at the
    beginning of the "N@{u}i@{uu}ckname" field. If the subject at hand, i.e., the
    person you are currently registering in the database, has a nickname
    you are aware of, just write it here and then press <ENTER>. You will
    notice that the cursor now moves to the beginning of the "@{u}E@{uu}-mail" field.
    If there is no nickname to enter into the database you can of course
    press <ENTER> without entering any data in the "N@{u}i@{uu}ckname" field and
    still end up in the "@{u}E@{uu}-mail" field. You don't @{u}have@{uu} to input any data in
    all the fields. In fact, you don't have to input any data in any field
    at all, but what would be the point of an entry containing no data? :)

    There is no need for you to enter the data in the order I suggested
    above, you are free to click with your mouse in any field whenever you
    choose. You can also enter the fields by pressing the underlined key of
    the field you want to access. The only thing you have to remember is
    that you must press <ENTER> after you have inserted any data, otherwise
    it won't be registered in the database.

    Finally, you can either choose to insert the entry you have created
    into your database by choosing "@{u}O@{uu}K" or you can skip the entry, i.e., 
    throw it in the waste-basket, by choosing "@{u}C@{uu}ancel".

    Once you have clicked "@{u}O@{uu}K", that is if you want to store the entry, the
    record is entered into the database which then instantly saves itself to
    your harddisk/floppy disk. In other words, you NEVER have to worry about
    saving your data to a disk, it is done automatically the split-second
    you press "@{u}O@{uu}K".

@endnode

@node The_Edit_Window "The Edit Window"
@next The_Show_Window
@prev The_New_Window
@toc  Main

				@{b}The Edit Window@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    This window looks almost exactly like the @{"New Window" link The_New_Window} and its purpose is
    @{u}almost@{uu} the same. You see, there is a difference. That's why they both
    exist, and not just one of them.

    Occasionally, because of changes in your life or in your friends' lives,
    you need to update the database. Perhaps your uncle has moved and he has
    a new address or maybe your grand-mother (!) has bought a cellular phone.
    Events like these make the information you have stored in your database
    obsolete and/or erroneous. You need to alter the data. You need to @{u}Edit@{uu}
    the data.

    To do so, select the entry you wish to change in the listview and click
    the "@{u}E@{uu}dit" button. Now, the Edit Window will appear on your screen.
    You will notice that some of (or all) the fields are occupied by all
    kinds of data. This is the information you registered in the database
    when you created this particular record, i.e., when you inserted this
    particular person into your database.

    Now all you have to do is access the fields you wish to edit, perform
    the changes, press <ENTER> after every change and then trigger the "@{u}O@{uu}K"
    button to store the changes in the database. If you do not wish to make
    the changes permanent, just trigger "@{u}C@{uu}ancel" instead.

    Once you have clicked "@{u}O@{uu}K", that is if you want to store the changes, 
    the record is entered into the database which then instantly saves it-
    self to your harddisk/floppy disk. In other words, you NEVER have to 
    worry about saving your data to a disk, it is done automatically the 
    split-second you press "@{u}O@{uu}K".

@endnode

@node The_Show_Window "The Show Window"
@next Sorting
@prev The_Edit_Window
@toc  Main

				@{b}The Show Window@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    To reach this window you have to select the record you wish to explore
    and trigger the "@{u}S@{uu}how" button. You can also just double-click the record
    in the listview and you will automatically be transferred to the Show
    Window.

    The main purpose of this window is to provide you with an easy way to
    find out what you have stored about a certain person in your database.
    I imagine this is the window you will use the most. The whole meaning 
    of @{b}Address@{ub} is to help you organize all the addresses, telephone numbers, 
    et cetera, that today lie on your desk in a very non-organized fashion. 
    However, there would be no sense in registering all these addresses and 
    numbers in the database if you couldn't access the data in a very easy 
    way, would there?

    Well, ta-da! Here is your data! Just enter the Show Window and you'll
    see what you have stored in the database about this particular person.
    Can it be any easier? I don't think so. :)

@endnode

@node Sorting "Strange Sorting"
@next Author
@prev The_Show_Window
@toc  Main

				@{b}Strange Sorting@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    If you are using AmigaOS 2.1 or higher and have chosen either "Svenska",
    "Deutsch" or "Norsk" as your default language in @{b}Locale@{ub}, or you speak
    Ēslenska and haven't found any "Ēslenska.language" on your "@{b}Locale:@{ub}" disk, 
    there exists a high probability that the sorting of the names in the 
    listview is not totally correct. The reason for this is that Commodore 
    released incorrect "#?.language" files. The "<yourlanguage>.language"
    file is the one that resides in "@{b}Locale:Languages/@{ub}" and it controls
    various localized settings, like the proper spelling of the weekdays in
    your language. If the file that is installed in your system is any of
    the ones listed below, you should replace it with the correct one that
    is included in this archive. If you speak Ēslenska you can also find a
    correct "Ēslenska.language" file in this package.
    The faulty files in question are:

    svenska.language, version 38.5 (12.3.92), which was compiled on the
    6th of July 1994 and has the size of 1056 bytes.

    deutsch.language, version 38.4 (30.3.92), which was compiled on the
    6th of July 1994 and has the size of 1068 bytes.

    norsk.language, version 38.4 (7.4.92), which was compiled on the
    6th of July 1994 and has the size of 1052 bytes.

@endnode

@node Author "The Author"
@next Bugs
@prev Sorting
@toc  Main

				@{b}The Author@{ub}
				@{b}~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

    Well, the author is me, Kristoffer Larsson. I am currently 21 years old 
    and live in Stockholm, the capital of Sweden. I'm studying Computer and 
    System Sciences at the Stockholm University and hope to become a skilled 
    computer wizard in a few years.

    I am very fond of programming, but I prefer the third generation of
    programming languages, like C or Pascal; 4GLs are not of any interest
    to me. However, I find the particular fourth-generation language SQL
    (Structured Query Language) rather okay to play around with. The third
    generation language HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is pretty nice too,
    I use it all the time when I'm updating my homepage.

    When it comes to computers, I have an Amiga 1200 and I'm very proud of
    it. In school I'm forced to use Macintosh, PC and UNIX (which is much
    better than the first two ones) but the Amiga is and always will be in
    the core of my heart. However, I am not one of those Amiga fanatics that
    won't even touch a computer of another brand; I love computers too much
    for that. ;-)

    The Star Wars Trilogy are the greatest movies ever done and George Lucas
    the greatest filmmaker in the world. I guess you could say I am a Star 
    Wars fanatic, but I won't let it control my life. Not that much, anyway.

    I also believe Michael Jackson is one of the greatest entertainers of
    all time; unfortunately his latter albums have not been that great. :(

    I have a web site on the Internet where you can find more information
    about me, about Star Wars, about movies in general, and about a lot of
    other things.

    The URL (Uniform Resource Locator) to my home page is:

    http://www.nada.kth.se/~d95-kla

    Please feel free to stop by any time!

    If you'd like to contact me, which you do if you consider using @{b}Address@{ub}
    regularly since the program is @{b}E-mailware@{ub}, these are a couple of
    addresses that might be of use:

    E-mail: kris-lar@dsv.su.se
            d95-kla@nada.kth.se

    Fidonet: 2:201/506.42

    When you have used @{b}Address@{ub} a couple of minutes and are just beginning to 
    realize the enormous potential of the program and how deeply it will 
    affect and serve you in years to come, you might want to express your 
    extensive graditude to me by sending me some money, computers, cars or 
    anything else appropriate. To do so, you will need my snail-mail address. 
    So, I guess I'll have to give it to you:

    Kristoffer Larsson
